1
00:00:00,080 --> 00:00:04,189
You do not need to configure every feature before starting.

2
00:00:04,189 --> 00:00:08,298
A useful first QualCanvas project needs a clear study name,

3
00:00:08,298 --> 00:00:12,407
one research question and one synthetic or properly approved source

4
00:00:12,407 --> 00:00:13,640
to practise with.

5
00:00:14,040 --> 00:00:17,709
You can begin on the free plan without a card.

6
00:00:17,709 --> 00:00:21,377
Check the current plan limits before importing a large study,

7
00:00:21,377 --> 00:00:25,046
and use an institutional route when governance or team controls

8
00:00:25,046 --> 00:00:26,880
are part of the protocol.

9
00:00:27,280 --> 00:00:30,730
The canvas list is your project home.

10
00:00:30,730 --> 00:00:35,660
Use a specific name that another researcher will recognise, especially

11
00:00:35,660 --> 00:00:40,096
when you expect several phases, samples or analytic approaches.

12
00:00:40,496 --> 00:00:44,566
Create a blank canvas when the structure should emerge from the material.

13
00:00:44,566 --> 00:00:47,957
Use a template when you want a starting codebook or

14
00:00:47,957 --> 00:00:51,349
workflow, then edit it to match the study rather than

15
00:00:51,349 --> 00:00:53,384
treating it as a fixed method.

16
00:00:53,784 --> 00:00:57,160
The left navigator tracks codes and sources.

17
00:00:57,160 --> 00:01:00,053
The centre is the spatial canvas.

18
00:01:00,053 --> 00:01:04,876
Primary actions sit across the top, while the status bar

19
00:01:04,876 --> 00:01:09,216
shows connection, save state, zoom and the command shortcut.

20
00:01:09,616 --> 00:01:12,711
If the interface feels dense, open Help.

21
00:01:12,711 --> 00:01:17,133
Take the product tour, view the keyboard shortcuts or open

22
00:01:17,133 --> 00:01:18,460
the complete guide.

23
00:01:18,460 --> 00:01:22,881
Learn one outcome at a time instead of trying to

24
00:01:22,881 --> 00:01:24,208
memorise every menu.

25
00:01:24,608 --> 00:01:28,808
A successful first session ends with one canvas, one source,

26
00:01:28,808 --> 00:01:33,008
one code and one short memo about what you noticed.

27
00:01:33,008 --> 00:01:38,048
That is enough to understand the core loop and return with confidence.
